{"title_page": "Carapinheira", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name      = Carapinheira\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = \n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Regi\u00e3o de Coimbra]]\n|district           = [[Coimbra District|Coimbra]]\n|municipality       = [[Montemor-o-Velho]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|40.209|-8.653|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|area_total         = 15.90\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 2898\n|patron             = \n|area_code          = \n|postal_code        = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Carapinheira''' is a [[towns of Portugal|town]] in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 2,898,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 15.90&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Montemor-o-Velho]]\n\n\n{{Coimbra-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name      = Carapinheira\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = \n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Regi\u00e3o de Coimbra]]\n|district           = [[Coimbra District|Coimbra]]\n|municipality       = [[Montemor-o-Velho]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|40.209|-8.653|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|area_total         = 15.90\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 2898\n|patron             = \n|area_code          = \n|postal_code        = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Carapinheira''' is a [[towns of Portugal|town]] in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 2,898,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 15.90&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Montemor-o-Velho]]\n\n\n{{Coimbra-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carapinheira"}
{"title_page": "2018 Horizon Air Q400 incident", "text_new": "{{short description|Aircraft crash in United States, August 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}} \n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = 2018 Horizon Air Q400 incident\n| occurrence_type = Incident\n| image = File:N449QX LAX (31294957790).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| alt =\n| caption = N449QX, the aircraft involved in the incident, pictured in 2015\n| date = August 10, 2018\n| type = Incident\n| Site = [[Ketron Island, Washington|Ketron Island]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], United States\n| coordinates = {{coordinates|47.148056|N|122.637500|W|type:event|display = inline,title}}<ref name=\"NTSB Report\">{{Cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20180812X92421&AKey=1&RType=Prelim&IType=FA|title=National Transportation Safety Board Aviation Accident Preliminary Report Accident Number: WPR18FA220|date=Aug 10, 2018|website=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|archive-url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Incident_WPR18FA220_National_Transportation_Safety_Board_Horizon_Air_De_Havilland_DHC-8-402,_N449QX_Q400.pdf|archive-date=Aug 17, 2018|url-status=|access-date=Aug 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| summary = Aircraft theft and suicide\n| aircraft_type = [[Bombardier Dash 8#Series 400|Bombardier Dash 8 Q400]]\n| Origin = [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]]\n| stopover =\n| stopover0 =\n| last_stopover =\n| Destination =\n| aircraft_name =\n| operator =<!--Horizon Air did not operate this flight. They owned the plane.-->\n| tail_number = N449QX\n| occupants = 1\n| fatalities = 1\n| survivors = 0\n}}\nOn August 10, 2018, a [[Horizon Air]] [[Bombardier Dash 8#Series 400|Bombardier Dash 8 Q400]] was stolen from [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] (Sea\u2013Tac) in [[SeaTac, Washington]]. The perpetrator, 29-year-old Richard Russell, was a Horizon Air ground service agent with no piloting experience. He performed an unauthorized takeoff and two  [[McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle]] fighters were subsequently [[Scrambling (military)|scrambled]] to intercept the aircraft. Sea\u2013Tac air traffic control made radio contact with Russell, the sole occupant, who described himself as a \"broken guy, got a few screws loose, I guess.\" Approximately one hour and 15 minutes after takeoff, Russell committed suicide by intentionally crashing the aircraft on the lightly-populated [[Ketron Island, Washington|Ketron Island]] in [[Puget Sound]].\n\n==Aircraft==\nThe incident aircraft was a [[Bombardier Dash 8#Series 400|Bombardier Dash 8 Q400]], owned by [[Horizon Air]] (and operating for [[Alaska Airlines]]) with the [[aircraft registration|registration]] N449QX<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/update-on-investigation-into-unauthorized-flight|title=Update on Investigation into Unauthorized Flight|last=Dietrich-Williams|first=Ayn|date=2018-08-15|website=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|language=en-us|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Stewart |first=Ashley |date=August 10, 2018 |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2018/08/10/horizon-jet-crashes-after-being-stolen-by-sea-tac.html |title=Alaska Air Horizon plane crashes after being stolen by airline employee |work=[[Puget Sound Business Journal]]|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ASN\">{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20180810-0|title=N449QX Criminal Occurrence description|last=|first=|date=|website=aviation-safety.net|publisher=[[Aviation Safety Network]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> and [[manufacturer's serial number|serial number]] 4410. It had first flown in 2012 and was delivered new to Horizon Air in the same year.<ref name=ASN/> The same aircraft landed at Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport at 13:35 local time the afternoon of the incident, after an in-service flight from [[Victoria, British Columbia]].<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |last=Day |first=Matt |date=August 11, 2018 |title=\"We were all screaming, 'Oh my god'\": How the Horizon Air theft and crash unfolded |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/we-were-all-screaming-oh-my-god%E2%80%8A-how-the-horizon-air-theft-and-crash-unfolded/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> It was not scheduled to fly again that day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/live-updates-airplane-taken-from-seattle-tacoma-international-airport-crashes/|title=How it unfolded: Full coverage of the Horizon Air crash and the man who stole the plane from Sea-Tac|last=Seattle Times staff|first=news services|date=2018-08-10|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\n[[File:Cropped chart of KSEA (northern end, from top of airport to Cargo 3).png|thumb|260px|Chart of the far northern end of Seattle\u2013Tacoma International, showing the location of Cargo 1 and runway 16C.]]\n{{maplink\n|frame=yes\n|frame-width=250\n|frame-height=350\n|zoom=8\n|frame-coord={{coord|47.463|N|122.437|W}}\n|type=point|coord={{coord|47.448784|N|122.308018|W}}\n|title=Sea-Tac Airport\n|type2=point|coord2={{coord|47.157331|N|122.633790|W}}\n|title2=Ketron Island\n|text=Location of Seattle-Tacoma International Airport (north) and Ketron Island (south) within northwestern Washington state.\n}}\nThe aircraft was stolen from Plane Cargo 1 at thc Airport<ref name=\":0\" /> and maneuvered to runway 16C via taxiways.<ref name=\"Times\" /> Seattle Tower tried several times to get the aircraft to identify itself on frequency; there was no response.<ref name=\"Times\" /> A nearby Alaska Airlines jet on the ground reported that the aircraft had begun a takeoff roll with its wheels smoking,<ref name=\"Times\" /> and an unauthorized take-off was made at 19:32 [[UTC-7|local time]] (02:32 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]], August 11).<ref name=\"NTSB Report\" /><ref name=BBC45153535 /><ref name=\"Sky114769728\">{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/unauthorised-take-off-of-plane-in-seattle-11469728|title=Stolen plane was chased by military jets before it crashed|last1=Bethany|first1=Bethany|last2=Marris|first2=Sharon|date=August 11, 2018|website=news.sky.com|publisher=[[Sky News]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=4bc36d84&opt=0|title=Crash: Horizon DH8D at Ketron Island on Aug 10th 2018, stolen aircraft crashed into forest|last=Hradecky|first=Simon|date=August 11, 2018|website=avherald.com|publisher=[[The Aviation Herald]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> In response, two [[McDonnell Douglas F-15C Eagle]]s of the [[Oregon Air National Guard]]'s [[142nd Fighter Wing]] under the command of [[NORAD]]<ref name=\"NORAD Command\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45153535 |title=Stolen plane closes Seattle-Tacoma airport before crashing |date=August 11, 2018 |website=BBC |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> were scrambled at around 20:15 local time<ref name=\"warzone\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/22807/oregon-f-15s-scramble-to-seattle-to-intercept-possibly-stolen-q400-airliner|title=Oregon F-15s Scramble To Seattle To Intercept Possibly Stolen Q400 Airliner (Updated)|last=Rogoway|first=Tyler|work=The Drive|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref> from [[Portland Air National Guard Base]] to intercept it. Both were armed with [[AIM-9 Sidewinder]] and [[AIM-120 AMRAAM]] [[air-to-air missile]]s<ref name=\"F-15Cs Intercept Stolen DASH-8 Airliner out of Seattle Tacoma Airport Before Crash.\">{{Cite web |url=https://theaviationist.com/2018/08/11/f-15cs-intercept-stolen-dash-8-airliner-out-of-seattle-tacoma-airport-before-crash/ |title=F-15Cs Intercept Stolen DASH-8 Airliner out of Seattle Tacoma Airport Before Crash. |last=Demerly |first=Tom |date=August 11, 2018 |website=The Aviationist |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> and went [[supersonic]], generating [[sonic boom]]s on the way to the Puget Sound area.<ref name=ASN/><ref name=ABC10>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc10.com/article/news/live-plane-stolen-from-sea-tac-airport-crashes-on-small-island-no-passengers-on-board/281-582563371 |title=LIVE: Plane stolen from Sea-Tac Airport crashes on small island; no passengers on board |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 10, 2018 |publisher=KXTV-TV |website=abc10.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416094713/http://abc10.com/article/news/local/horizon-air-employee-stole-crashed-plane-on-pierce-county-island/281-582563371 |archivedate=April 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[KC-135R Stratotanker]] refueling tanker was also scrambled from [[Fairchild Air Force Base]] to support the F-15 flight.<ref name=\"F-15Cs Intercept Stolen DASH-8 Airliner out of Seattle Tacoma Airport Before Crash.\"/> Flights in and out of the airport were temporarily suspended.<ref name=\"BBC45153535\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45153535|title='Stolen' plane closes Seattle airport before crashing into sea|last=|first=|date=|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeattle\u2013Tacoma air traffic control (ATC) maintained radio contact with the occupant.<ref name=\"Pilot wanted to do aerobatics, apologized for his actions as he spoke with air traffic control\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/article216506075.html|title=Pilot wanted to do aerobatics, apologized for his actions as he spoke with air traffic control|last=Sailor|first=Craig|date=August 11, 2018|website=The News Tribune|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> The transmissions were on an open frequency and were quickly posted on social media websites.<ref name=\"ATC Communications Posted Almost Immediately on Social Media\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2018/08/11/f-15cs-intercept-suicidal-pilot/|title=NORAD F-15Cs intercept suicidal pilot in dramatic chase near Seattle|last=Copp|first=Tara|date=August 11, 2018|website=Military Times|access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> He said he was a \"broken guy, got a few screws loose I guess. Never really knew it until now.\"<ref name=\"Passenger Plane Stolen by Employee Crashes on Island Near Seattle Airport\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/11/us/seattle-plane-crash-stolen.html|title=Passenger Plane Stolen by Employee Crashes on Island Near Seattle Airport|last=Fortin|first=Jacey|date=August 11, 2018|website=The New York Times|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> When ATC suggested that the plane be landed at [[Joint Base Lewis\u2013McChord]], the occupant refused: \"Those guys will rough me up if I try and land there. I think I might mess something up there, too. I wouldn't want to do that.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |last1=Miroff |first1=Nick |last2=Horton |first2=Alex |title=Seattle hijacker's plane heist, midair stunts and fiery crash expose gaps in aviation security |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/seattle-hijackers-plane-heist-midair-stunts-and-fatal-crash-expose-gaps-in-aviation-security/2018/08/11/1309e6f0-9d7a-11e8-b60b-1c897f17e185_story.html?noredirect=on |website=[[The Washington Post]] Online |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> He asked ATC if he could get a job as a pilot with Alaska Airlines if he successfully landed the aircraft. ATC said that \"they would give you a job doing anything if you could pull this off,\" to which he replied \"Yeah right! Nah, I'm a white guy.\"<ref name=heavy5/>\nHe spoke of wanting to do \"a couple maneuvers to see what [the aircraft] can do,\" and requested the coordinates of [[Tahlequah (orca)|an orca]] that had been brought to national attention, saying, \"I want to go see that guy.\" He stated that he did not want to hurt anyone,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"ABC13\">{{cite web|url=https://abc13.com/airline-worker-who-stole-plane-told-air-traffic-control-i-dont-want-to-hurt-no-one/3928151/|title=Airline worker who stole plane told air traffic control 'I don't want to hurt no one'|last=Cook|first=Jeffrey|date=August 11, 2018|website=abc13.com|publisher=KTRK-TV|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> and in the final minutes of the communication apologized to his friends and family.<ref name=\"ATC Communications Posted Almost Immediately on Social Media\"/> Near the end of the flight, the aircraft was filmed doing [[aerobatic maneuver]]s over [[Puget Sound]], footage of which appeared on social media.<ref name=\"Horizon Air Q400 Aircraft Crashes After Being Stolen From Seattle Airport\">{{Cite web |url=https://thepointsguy.com/news/horizon-air-q400-stolen-from-seattle/ |title=Horizon Air Q400 Aircraft Crashes After Being Stolen From Seattle Airport |last=Kheel |first=Julian |date=August 11, 2018 |website=The Points Guy |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> A veteran pilot said the maneuvers \"seemed pretty well executed, without either stalling or pulling the wings off.\"<ref name=\"SeaTac Hijacker Had the Skills to Take Out a Skyscraper\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/seatac-hijacker-had-the-skills-to-take-out-a-skyscraper?ref=home&via=twitter_page |title=SeaTac Hijacker Had the Skills to Take Out a Skyscraper Horizon Air ground handler Richard Russell knew how to fly without tearing the plane apart\u2014and enough fuel to be a flying bomb. How was he able to take off without being stopped? |last=Clive |first=Irving |date=August 12, 2018 |website=Daily Beast |access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> When an air traffic controller requested he land the plane after these maneuvers, he said \"I don't know. I don't want to. I was kind of hoping that was gonna be it, you know?\"<ref name=\"Passenger Plane Stolen by Employee Crashes on Island Near Seattle Airport\" /><ref name=\"ABC13\" /> He added that he \"wasn't really planning on landing it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/horizon-employee-conveyed-flying-knowledge-to-air-traffic-controllers-1534049609|title=Plane Thief Said He Trained on Games, Didn't Plan to Land|last1=Sider|first1=Alison|last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy|date=August 12, 2018|website=The Wall Street Journal|last3=Greene|first3=Jay}}</ref>\n\nThe two F-15s attempted to direct the aircraft toward the Pacific Ocean, and did not fire on it.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/norad-fighter-jets-were-trying-to-direct-stolen-plane-over-pacific-ocean-when-it-crashed/|title=NORAD: Fighter jets were trying to direct stolen plane over Pacific Ocean when it crashed|date=2018-08-11|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref> The Q400 ultimately crashed at 20:43 local time<ref name=\"NTSB Report\" /> on [[Ketron Island, Washington|Ketron Island]] in Puget Sound, [[Pierce County, Washington]], killing the occupant and destroying the aircraft.<ref name=\"ASN\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Herald\" /> A tow boat crew was the first to respond.<ref name=\"Tow Boat Crew First to Respond\">{{Cite web |url=http://mynorthwest.com/1076945/tow-boat-horizon-plane-crash-ketron/ |title=Towboat crew dropped everything to respond to Ketron Island crash |author=MyNorthWestStaff |date=August 11, 2018 |website=My Northwest |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> Firefighters from West Pierce Fire and Rescue and other nearby departments arrived on the island approximately 1.5 hours after the crash, due to waits for the [[Steilacoom\u2013Anderson Island ferry]], and contending with thick brush when crews arrived on scene. The two-acre fire the crash caused<ref name=\":1\" /> was suppressed by a lack of wind and dry brush, and was extinguished by the following morning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Misciagna |first=Vanessa |date=August 12, 2018 |title=Firefighters battle more than flames after Ketron Island plane crash |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/firefighters-battle-more-than-flames-after-ketron-island-plane-crash/281-583379352 |publisher=[[KING-TV]] |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pulkkinen |first=Levi |date=August 12, 2018 |title=Seattle plane crash: 'heartbroken' family remember gentle man who meant no harm |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/aug/11/seattle-airport-plane-theft-crash-fbi-investigation |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> No injuries were reported to residents of the sparsely populated island despite the crash site being in close proximity to at least one cabin which was occupied at the time of the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://komonews.com/news/local/ketron-island-residents-grateful-horizon-air-plane-didnt-crash-into-homes|title=Ketron Island residents grateful Horizon Air plane didn't crash into homes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe [[Pierce County Sheriff's Office]] both thanked the public for its accurate information, and acknowledged on August 11 that federal agencies would be leading the investigation, primarily the Seattle office of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI).<ref name=\"From the Pierce County Sheriff Official Twitter feed to the FBI.\">{{Cite tweet |number=1028172038655991808 |user=PierceSheriff |title=Thanks to everyone for sharing accurate information, insuring the public's safety. The federal agencies will lead the investigation. All further inquiries should be directed to the Seattle FBI office. |author=Pierce County Sheriff's Department |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> It described the perpetrator, identified as 29-year-old Richard Russell,<ref name=\"Newsweek\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Airplane taken from Seattle-Tacoma International Airport has crashed |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/airplane-taken-from-seattle-tacoma-international-airport-has-crashed/ |newspaper=Seattle Times |date=August 10, 2018}}</ref> as suicidal and said his actions did not constitute a \"terrorist incident\".<ref name=\"ABC13\"/> Alaska Air Group CEO [[Brad Tilden]] announced on the same day that the airline was coordinating with the [[Federal Aviation Administration]], the FBI, and the [[National Transportation Safety Board]], and was \"working to find out everything we possibly can about what happened\".<ref name=\"Alaska Airlines Group CEO statement\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/08/11/breaking-news/authorities-probe-how-suicidal-employee-could-steal-plane-from-seattle-airport/ |title=Authorities probe how 'suicidal' employee could steal plane from Seattle airport |date=August 11, 2018 |website=Honolulu Star Advertiser |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Initial FBI Statement`\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/fbi-seeks-motive-after-us-airline-worker-stole-plane-and-crashed-it |title=Man who sought 'serenity' before crashing stolen plane near Seattle is identified |date=August 11, 2018 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> On August 12, the FBI said that it had recovered the flight data recorder along with components of the cockpit voice recorder. The equipment was sent to the National Transportation Safety Board for processing.<ref name=usatoday>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2018/08/13/stolen-plane-human-remains-black-box-found-seattle-plane/974631002/ |title=Human remains, black box found from plane stolen by Seattle airport employee |date=August 13, 2018  |website=USA Today |access-date=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 9, the FBI stated that it had completed its investigation. Terrorism was ruled out and it was found that Russell had acted alone. The final descent at Ketron Island was determined to be intentional, and [[suicide]] was listed as the manner of death.<ref name=FBI>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/fbi-completes-investigation-into-august-2018-unauthorized-flight-from-seattle-tacoma-airport |title=FBI Completes Investigation into August 2018 Unauthorized Flight from Seattle-Tacoma Airport |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation |location=Seattle, Washington |accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-09/horizon-air-worker-who-stole-crashed-plane-intended-suicide|title =Horizon Air Worker Who Crashed Plane Bent on Suicide, Not Terror|first =Alan|last =Levin|website =Bloomberg|date =November 9, 2018}}</ref> The FBI stated, \"Interviews with work colleagues, friends, and family\u2014and review of text messages exchanged with Russell during the incident\u2014did not identify any information that would suggest the theft of the aircraft was related to wider criminal activity or terrorist ideology. Although investigators received information regarding Russell's background, possible stressors, and personal life, no element provided a clear motivation for Russell's actions.\"<ref name=FBI/>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n\nRichard Russell was a Horizon Air [[Pushback|ground service agent]] from [[Sumner, Washington]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |title=Seattle: stolen plane crashes after rogue take-off from Sea-Tac airport |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/11/seatac-airport-seattle-plane-takes-off-without-permission |newspaper=The Guardian |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> He had been part of a [[Pushback|tow]] team, which repositions aircraft on the [[airport apron]], for about four years.<ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/ground-service-suicide-horizon-air-seatac-hijacker-plane-1069656 |title=ALASKA AIRLINES: EVERYTHING WE KNOW ABOUT THE SUICIDAL HIJACKER |last=Kogan |first=Danielle |date=August 11, 2018 |website=Newsweek |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> An operational supervisor for Horizon Air described Russell as \"a quiet guy\" who was \"well liked by the other workers\".<ref name=quiet/> During his communication with air traffic control Russell made a complaint about wages, stating: \"Minimum wage, we'll chalk it up to that. Maybe that will grease some gears a little bit with the higher-ups.\"<ref name=st19>{{cite web|url =https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/he-was-a-jokester-who-complained-about-his-job-but-friends-still-baffled-by-richard-russells-airplane-heist/|title =Richard Russell was a jokester who complained about work, but Sea-Tac plane heist still baffles friends|website =The Seattle Times|first1 =David|last1 =Gutman|first2 =Hal|last2 =Bernton|date =August 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRussell was born in [[Key West, Florida]], and moved to [[Wasilla, Alaska]], at the age of seven.<ref name=quiet>{{cite news |title=Man who took Horizon Air plane from Sea-Tac Airport was quiet, well liked, says former co-worker |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/man-who-took-horizon-air-plane-from-sea-tac-airport-was-quiet-well-liked-says-former-co-worker/ |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Wasilla High School]], where he wrestled and competed in track and field.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/08/12/family-man-who-stole-plane-at-sea-tac-express-shock-others-say-beebo-was-friendly-guy.html|title =Family of man who stole plane at Sea-Tac express 'shock,' others say 'Beebo' was friendly guy|publisher =Fox News|first =Bradford|last =Betz|date =August 12, 2018}}</ref>\nHe was known as \"Beebo\" to his friends and family.<ref name=time/> He had been married since 2012; he met his wife in 2011 at a [[Campus Crusade for Christ]] meeting at [[Southwestern Oregon Community College]]. Together they started a bakery in [[North Bend, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theworldlink.com/new-bakery-is-a-labor-of-love/article_b19316e0-7ce6-11e1-bc81-001a4bcf887a.html |title=New bakery is a labor of love |author=Staff writer(s) |website=[[The World (Coos Bay)|The World]] |date=April 2, 2012}}</ref> They sold the bakery in 2015 so his wife could be closer to her family; they settled in Sumner, Washington, and Russell found employment with Horizon Air.<ref name=time>{{cite web|url =http://time.com/5364913/richard-russel-seattle-horizon-air-stolen-plane/|title ='Beebo Was Loved By Everyone.' Family Left Heartbroken After Airline Worker Steals and Crashes Plane|website =Time|first =Alix|last =Langone|date =August 12, 2018}}</ref>\nHe was an avid traveler and attended [[Washington State University Global Campus]], majoring in social science. He had planned to seek a management position at Horizon Air or become a military officer after receiving his degree.<ref name=heavy5>{{cite web |url=https://heavy.com/news/2018/08/richard-russell-rich-seatac-beebo/ |title=Richard Russell, 'Rich': 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |author=Jessica McBride |publisher=Heavy.com}}</ref> He was active in his church and a leader in the local Christian youth ministry [[Young Life]].<ref name=quiet/>\n\nHorizon Air CEO Gary Beck stated that, as far as the company knew, Russell did not have a [[pilot's license]]. Beck said the aerial maneuvers were \"incredible\" and that he \"did not know how [Russell] achieved the experience that he did.\"<ref name=CBS>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/richard-russell-seatac-horizon-air-stolen-plane-crash-seatac-airport-authorities-no-pilot-license-2018-08-11/  |title=Authorities don't believe man who stole plane had a pilot's license |publisher=CBS |accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> During his conversation with air traffic control, Russell said he \"[knew] what [he was] doing a little bit\" because he had experience playing video games.<ref name=heavy5/> After the incident, Joel Monteith, a pilot for [[SkyWest Airlines]], relayed to an emergency dispatcher that in 2017 he saw Russell and another man \"pointing and flipping switches\" in the cockpit of a SkyWest aircraft parked at Sea\u2013Tac Airport. Monteith stated the men told him they were training to use the aircraft's [[auxiliary power unit]] so they could tow it, but said it was \"suspicious\" that they left when he confronted them. Monteith also recalled that Russell had been in the cockpit of an [[Embraer E-Jet family#E175|Embraer 175]] with him, and that Russell asked him about his \"flows, which is the preflight preparation I do for takeoff.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/pilot-became-suspicious-of-richard-russell-a-year-before-he-stole-airplane-from-sea-tac/|title =\u2018Airplane of opportunity\u2019? Richard Russell raised pilot's suspicions a year before Sea-Tac plane heist|first =Lewis|last =Kamb|website =The Seattle Times|date =September 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the incident, observers on internet forums began referring to Russell as \"Sky King\" as a tribute to his ability at flying the aircraft, as well as his actions during the incident.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Glenn |title=The Sky King of Sea-Tac Airport |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/gb/blog/acquainted-the-night/201809/the-sky-king-sea-tac-airport |website=[[Psychology Today]] |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRussell's family released a statement on August 11, stating they were \"stunned and heartbroken\" and \"devastated by the events\".<ref name=\"Family statement\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/who-was-richard-russell-things-know/DDH7SU1hCUPNgmFEyWSfYO/ |title=Who was Richard Russell? 7 things to know  |last=D'Angelo |first=Bob |date=August 12, 2018 |website=AJC |access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nIn the days after the crash, clean up and recovery crews contracted by Alaska Airlines and their insurers were present on the island to remove debris. As of 2019, this clean up effort was still ongoing with pieces of aircraft wreckage still being located on the island after the first anniversary of the incident. Residents of the island bore some of the cost for cleaning up, and as of 2019 negotiations were under way for their reimbursement by Alaska Airlines insurers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/one-year-after-stolen-horizon-plane-crash-scars-remain-on-ketron-island/ar-AAFy232|title=One year after stolen Horizon plane crash, scars remain on Ketron Island|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2003 Angola 727 disappearance]], another (presumed) instance of aircraft theft\n*[[1999 Air Botswana ATR 42 crash]], an instance of an employee stealing an aircraft and crashing it\n\n{{Portalbar|United States|Aviation}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LeYVtVg6aGs Compilation of footage of the aircraft being flown erratically in the vicinity of Seattle, and the pursuing F-15s]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-GzroZxwhJg ATC Recording]\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horizon Air Q400 incident}}\n[[Category:2018 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:2018 in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Bombardier Dash 8]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents involving deliberate crashes]]\n[[Category:August 2018 crimes in North America]]\n[[Category:August 2018 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the United States in 2018]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aircraft crash in United States, August 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}} \n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = 2018 Horizon Air Q400 incident\n| occurrence_type = Incident\n| image = File:N449QX LAX (31294957790).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| alt =\n| caption = N449QX, the aircraft involved in the incident, pictured in 2015\n| date = August 10, 2018\n| type = Incident\n| Site = [[Ketron Island, Washington|Ketron Island]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], United States\n| coordinates = {{coordinates|47.148056|N|122.637500|W|type:event|display = inline,title}}<ref name=\"NTSB Report\">{{Cite web|url=https://app.ntsb.gov/pdfgenerator/ReportGeneratorFile.ashx?EventID=20180812X92421&AKey=1&RType=Prelim&IType=FA|title=National Transportation Safety Board Aviation Accident Preliminary Report Accident Number: WPR18FA220|date=Aug 10, 2018|website=[[National Transportation Safety Board]]|archive-url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Incident_WPR18FA220_National_Transportation_Safety_Board_Horizon_Air_De_Havilland_DHC-8-402,_N449QX_Q400.pdf|archive-date=Aug 17, 2018|url-status=|access-date=Aug 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| summary = Aircraft theft and suicide\n| aircraft_type = [[Bombardier Dash 8#Series 400|Bombardier Dash 8 Q400]]\n| Origin = [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]]\n| stopover =\n| stopover0 =\n| last_stopover =\n| Destination =\n| aircraft_name =\n| operator =<!--Horizon Air did not operate this flight. They owned the plane.-->\n| tail_number = N449QX\n| occupants = 1\n| fatalities = 1\n| survivors = 0\n}}\nOn August 10, 2018, a [[Horizon Air]] [[Bombardier Dash 8#Series 400|Bombardier Dash 8 Q400]] was stolen from [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] (Sea\u2013Tac) in [[SeaTac, Washington]]. The perpetrator, 29-year-old Richard Russell, was a Horizon Air ground service agent with no piloting experience. He performed an unauthorized takeoff and two  [[McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle]] fighters were subsequently [[Scrambling (military)|scrambled]] to intercept the aircraft. Sea\u2013Tac air traffic control made radio contact with Russell, the sole occupant, who described himself as a \"broken guy, got a few screws loose, I guess.\" Approximately one hour and 15 minutes after takeoff, Russell committed suicide by intentionally crashing the aircraft on the lightly-populated [[Ketron Island, Washington|Ketron Island]] in [[Puget Sound]].\n\n==Aircraft==\nThe incident aircraft was a [[Bombardier Dash 8#Series 400|Bombardier Dash 8 Q400]], owned by [[Horizon Air]] (and operating for [[Alaska Airlines]]) with the [[aircraft registration|registration]] N449QX<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/update-on-investigation-into-unauthorized-flight|title=Update on Investigation into Unauthorized Flight|last=Dietrich-Williams|first=Ayn|date=2018-08-15|website=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|language=en-us|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Stewart |first=Ashley |date=August 10, 2018 |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2018/08/10/horizon-jet-crashes-after-being-stolen-by-sea-tac.html |title=Alaska Air Horizon plane crashes after being stolen by airline employee |work=[[Puget Sound Business Journal]]|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ASN\">{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20180810-0|title=N449QX Criminal Occurrence description|last=|first=|date=|website=aviation-safety.net|publisher=[[Aviation Safety Network]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> and [[manufacturer's serial number|serial number]] 4410. It had first flown in 2012 and was delivered new to Horizon Air in the same year.<ref name=ASN/> The same aircraft landed at Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport at 13:35 local time the afternoon of the incident, after an in-service flight from [[Victoria, British Columbia]].<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |last=Day |first=Matt |date=August 11, 2018 |title=\"We were all screaming, 'Oh my god'\": How the Horizon Air theft and crash unfolded |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/we-were-all-screaming-oh-my-god%E2%80%8A-how-the-horizon-air-theft-and-crash-unfolded/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> It was not scheduled to fly again that day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/live-updates-airplane-taken-from-seattle-tacoma-international-airport-crashes/|title=How it unfolded: Full coverage of the Horizon Air crash and the man who stole the plane from Sea-Tac|last=Seattle Times staff|first=news services|date=2018-08-10|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\n[[File:Cropped chart of KSEA (northern end, from top of airport to Cargo 3).png|thumb|260px|Chart of the far northern end of Seattle\u2013Tacoma International, showing the location of Cargo 1 and runway 16C.]]\n{{maplink\n|frame=yes\n|frame-width=250\n|frame-height=350\n|zoom=8\n|frame-coord={{coord|47.463|N|122.437|W}}\n|type=point|coord={{coord|47.448784|N|122.308018|W}}\n|title=Sea-Tac Airport\n|type2=point|coord2={{coord|47.157331|N|122.633790|W}}\n|title2=Ketron Island\n|text=Location of Seattle-Tacoma International Airport (north) and Ketron Island (south) within northwestern Washington state.\n}}\nThe aircraft was stolen from Plane Cargo 1 at the north end of Sea\u2013Tac Airport<ref name=\":0\" /> and maneuvered to runway 16C via taxiways.<ref name=\"Times\" /> Seattle Tower tried several times to get the aircraft to identify itself on frequency; there was no response.<ref name=\"Times\" /> A nearby Alaska Airlines jet on the ground reported that the aircraft had begun a takeoff roll with its wheels smoking,<ref name=\"Times\" /> and an unauthorized take-off was made at 19:32 [[UTC-7|local time]] (02:32 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]], August 11).<ref name=\"NTSB Report\" /><ref name=BBC45153535 /><ref name=\"Sky114769728\">{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/unauthorised-take-off-of-plane-in-seattle-11469728|title=Stolen plane was chased by military jets before it crashed|last1=Bethany|first1=Bethany|last2=Marris|first2=Sharon|date=August 11, 2018|website=news.sky.com|publisher=[[Sky News]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite web|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=4bc36d84&opt=0|title=Crash: Horizon DH8D at Ketron Island on Aug 10th 2018, stolen aircraft crashed into forest|last=Hradecky|first=Simon|date=August 11, 2018|website=avherald.com|publisher=[[The Aviation Herald]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> In response, two [[McDonnell Douglas F-15C Eagle]]s of the [[Oregon Air National Guard]]'s [[142nd Fighter Wing]] under the command of [[NORAD]]<ref name=\"NORAD Command\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45153535 |title=Stolen plane closes Seattle-Tacoma airport before crashing |date=August 11, 2018 |website=BBC |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> were scrambled at around 20:15 local time<ref name=\"warzone\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/22807/oregon-f-15s-scramble-to-seattle-to-intercept-possibly-stolen-q400-airliner|title=Oregon F-15s Scramble To Seattle To Intercept Possibly Stolen Q400 Airliner (Updated)|last=Rogoway|first=Tyler|work=The Drive|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref> from [[Portland Air National Guard Base]] to intercept it. Both were armed with [[AIM-9 Sidewinder]] and [[AIM-120 AMRAAM]] [[air-to-air missile]]s<ref name=\"F-15Cs Intercept Stolen DASH-8 Airliner out of Seattle Tacoma Airport Before Crash.\">{{Cite web |url=https://theaviationist.com/2018/08/11/f-15cs-intercept-stolen-dash-8-airliner-out-of-seattle-tacoma-airport-before-crash/ |title=F-15Cs Intercept Stolen DASH-8 Airliner out of Seattle Tacoma Airport Before Crash. |last=Demerly |first=Tom |date=August 11, 2018 |website=The Aviationist |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> and went [[supersonic]], generating [[sonic boom]]s on the way to the Puget Sound area.<ref name=ASN/><ref name=ABC10>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc10.com/article/news/live-plane-stolen-from-sea-tac-airport-crashes-on-small-island-no-passengers-on-board/281-582563371 |title=LIVE: Plane stolen from Sea-Tac Airport crashes on small island; no passengers on board |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 10, 2018 |publisher=KXTV-TV |website=abc10.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416094713/http://abc10.com/article/news/local/horizon-air-employee-stole-crashed-plane-on-pierce-county-island/281-582563371 |archivedate=April 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[KC-135R Stratotanker]] refueling tanker was also scrambled from [[Fairchild Air Force Base]] to support the F-15 flight.<ref name=\"F-15Cs Intercept Stolen DASH-8 Airliner out of Seattle Tacoma Airport Before Crash.\"/> Flights in and out of the airport were temporarily suspended.<ref name=\"BBC45153535\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-45153535|title='Stolen' plane closes Seattle airport before crashing into sea|last=|first=|date=|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeattle\u2013Tacoma air traffic control (ATC) maintained radio contact with the occupant.<ref name=\"Pilot wanted to do aerobatics, apologized for his actions as he spoke with air traffic control\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/article216506075.html|title=Pilot wanted to do aerobatics, apologized for his actions as he spoke with air traffic control|last=Sailor|first=Craig|date=August 11, 2018|website=The News Tribune|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> The transmissions were on an open frequency and were quickly posted on social media websites.<ref name=\"ATC Communications Posted Almost Immediately on Social Media\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2018/08/11/f-15cs-intercept-suicidal-pilot/|title=NORAD F-15Cs intercept suicidal pilot in dramatic chase near Seattle|last=Copp|first=Tara|date=August 11, 2018|website=Military Times|access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> He said he was a \"broken guy, got a few screws loose I guess. Never really knew it until now.\"<ref name=\"Passenger Plane Stolen by Employee Crashes on Island Near Seattle Airport\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/11/us/seattle-plane-crash-stolen.html|title=Passenger Plane Stolen by Employee Crashes on Island Near Seattle Airport|last=Fortin|first=Jacey|date=August 11, 2018|website=The New York Times|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> When ATC suggested that the plane be landed at [[Joint Base Lewis\u2013McChord]], the occupant refused: \"Those guys will rough me up if I try and land there. I think I might mess something up there, too. I wouldn't want to do that.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |last1=Miroff |first1=Nick |last2=Horton |first2=Alex |title=Seattle hijacker's plane heist, midair stunts and fiery crash expose gaps in aviation security |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/seattle-hijackers-plane-heist-midair-stunts-and-fatal-crash-expose-gaps-in-aviation-security/2018/08/11/1309e6f0-9d7a-11e8-b60b-1c897f17e185_story.html?noredirect=on |website=[[The Washington Post]] Online |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> He asked ATC if he could get a job as a pilot with Alaska Airlines if he successfully landed the aircraft. ATC said that \"they would give you a job doing anything if you could pull this off,\" to which he replied \"Yeah right! Nah, I'm a white guy.\"<ref name=heavy5/>\nHe spoke of wanting to do \"a couple maneuvers to see what [the aircraft] can do,\" and requested the coordinates of [[Tahlequah (orca)|an orca]] that had been brought to national attention, saying, \"I want to go see that guy.\" He stated that he did not want to hurt anyone,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"ABC13\">{{cite web|url=https://abc13.com/airline-worker-who-stole-plane-told-air-traffic-control-i-dont-want-to-hurt-no-one/3928151/|title=Airline worker who stole plane told air traffic control 'I don't want to hurt no one'|last=Cook|first=Jeffrey|date=August 11, 2018|website=abc13.com|publisher=KTRK-TV|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> and in the final minutes of the communication apologized to his friends and family.<ref name=\"ATC Communications Posted Almost Immediately on Social Media\"/> Near the end of the flight, the aircraft was filmed doing [[aerobatic maneuver]]s over [[Puget Sound]], footage of which appeared on social media.<ref name=\"Horizon Air Q400 Aircraft Crashes After Being Stolen From Seattle Airport\">{{Cite web |url=https://thepointsguy.com/news/horizon-air-q400-stolen-from-seattle/ |title=Horizon Air Q400 Aircraft Crashes After Being Stolen From Seattle Airport |last=Kheel |first=Julian |date=August 11, 2018 |website=The Points Guy |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> A veteran pilot said the maneuvers \"seemed pretty well executed, without either stalling or pulling the wings off.\"<ref name=\"SeaTac Hijacker Had the Skills to Take Out a Skyscraper\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/seatac-hijacker-had-the-skills-to-take-out-a-skyscraper?ref=home&via=twitter_page |title=SeaTac Hijacker Had the Skills to Take Out a Skyscraper Horizon Air ground handler Richard Russell knew how to fly without tearing the plane apart\u2014and enough fuel to be a flying bomb. How was he able to take off without being stopped? |last=Clive |first=Irving |date=August 12, 2018 |website=Daily Beast |access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> When an air traffic controller requested he land the plane after these maneuvers, he said \"I don't know. I don't want to. I was kind of hoping that was gonna be it, you know?\"<ref name=\"Passenger Plane Stolen by Employee Crashes on Island Near Seattle Airport\" /><ref name=\"ABC13\" /> He added that he \"wasn't really planning on landing it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/horizon-employee-conveyed-flying-knowledge-to-air-traffic-controllers-1534049609|title=Plane Thief Said He Trained on Games, Didn't Plan to Land|last1=Sider|first1=Alison|last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy|date=August 12, 2018|website=The Wall Street Journal|last3=Greene|first3=Jay}}</ref>\n\nThe two F-15s attempted to direct the aircraft toward the Pacific Ocean, and did not fire on it.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/norad-fighter-jets-were-trying-to-direct-stolen-plane-over-pacific-ocean-when-it-crashed/|title=NORAD: Fighter jets were trying to direct stolen plane over Pacific Ocean when it crashed|date=2018-08-11|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref> The Q400 ultimately crashed at 20:43 local time<ref name=\"NTSB Report\" /> on [[Ketron Island, Washington|Ketron Island]] in Puget Sound, [[Pierce County, Washington]], killing the occupant and destroying the aircraft.<ref name=\"ASN\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Herald\" /> A tow boat crew was the first to respond.<ref name=\"Tow Boat Crew First to Respond\">{{Cite web |url=http://mynorthwest.com/1076945/tow-boat-horizon-plane-crash-ketron/ |title=Towboat crew dropped everything to respond to Ketron Island crash |author=MyNorthWestStaff |date=August 11, 2018 |website=My Northwest |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> Firefighters from West Pierce Fire and Rescue and other nearby departments arrived on the island approximately 1.5 hours after the crash, due to waits for the [[Steilacoom\u2013Anderson Island ferry]], and contending with thick brush when crews arrived on scene. The two-acre fire the crash caused<ref name=\":1\" /> was suppressed by a lack of wind and dry brush, and was extinguished by the following morning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Misciagna |first=Vanessa |date=August 12, 2018 |title=Firefighters battle more than flames after Ketron Island plane crash |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/firefighters-battle-more-than-flames-after-ketron-island-plane-crash/281-583379352 |publisher=[[KING-TV]] |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pulkkinen |first=Levi |date=August 12, 2018 |title=Seattle plane crash: 'heartbroken' family remember gentle man who meant no harm |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/aug/11/seattle-airport-plane-theft-crash-fbi-investigation |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> No injuries were reported to residents of the sparsely populated island despite the crash site being in close proximity to at least one cabin which was occupied at the time of the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://komonews.com/news/local/ketron-island-residents-grateful-horizon-air-plane-didnt-crash-into-homes|title=Ketron Island residents grateful Horizon Air plane didn't crash into homes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe [[Pierce County Sheriff's Office]] both thanked the public for its accurate information, and acknowledged on August 11 that federal agencies would be leading the investigation, primarily the Seattle office of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI).<ref name=\"From the Pierce County Sheriff Official Twitter feed to the FBI.\">{{Cite tweet |number=1028172038655991808 |user=PierceSheriff |title=Thanks to everyone for sharing accurate information, insuring the public's safety. The federal agencies will lead the investigation. All further inquiries should be directed to the Seattle FBI office. |author=Pierce County Sheriff's Department |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> It described the perpetrator, identified as 29-year-old Richard Russell,<ref name=\"Newsweek\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Airplane taken from Seattle-Tacoma International Airport has crashed |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/airplane-taken-from-seattle-tacoma-international-airport-has-crashed/ |newspaper=Seattle Times |date=August 10, 2018}}</ref> as suicidal and said his actions did not constitute a \"terrorist incident\".<ref name=\"ABC13\"/> Alaska Air Group CEO [[Brad Tilden]] announced on the same day that the airline was coordinating with the [[Federal Aviation Administration]], the FBI, and the [[National Transportation Safety Board]], and was \"working to find out everything we possibly can about what happened\".<ref name=\"Alaska Airlines Group CEO statement\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/08/11/breaking-news/authorities-probe-how-suicidal-employee-could-steal-plane-from-seattle-airport/ |title=Authorities probe how 'suicidal' employee could steal plane from Seattle airport |date=August 11, 2018 |website=Honolulu Star Advertiser |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Initial FBI Statement`\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/fbi-seeks-motive-after-us-airline-worker-stole-plane-and-crashed-it |title=Man who sought 'serenity' before crashing stolen plane near Seattle is identified |date=August 11, 2018 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> On August 12, the FBI said that it had recovered the flight data recorder along with components of the cockpit voice recorder. The equipment was sent to the National Transportation Safety Board for processing.<ref name=usatoday>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2018/08/13/stolen-plane-human-remains-black-box-found-seattle-plane/974631002/ |title=Human remains, black box found from plane stolen by Seattle airport employee |date=August 13, 2018  |website=USA Today |access-date=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 9, the FBI stated that it had completed its investigation. Terrorism was ruled out and it was found that Russell had acted alone. The final descent at Ketron Island was determined to be intentional, and [[suicide]] was listed as the manner of death.<ref name=FBI>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/fbi-completes-investigation-into-august-2018-unauthorized-flight-from-seattle-tacoma-airport |title=FBI Completes Investigation into August 2018 Unauthorized Flight from Seattle-Tacoma Airport |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation |location=Seattle, Washington |accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-09/horizon-air-worker-who-stole-crashed-plane-intended-suicide|title =Horizon Air Worker Who Crashed Plane Bent on Suicide, Not Terror|first =Alan|last =Levin|website =Bloomberg|date =November 9, 2018}}</ref> The FBI stated, \"Interviews with work colleagues, friends, and family\u2014and review of text messages exchanged with Russell during the incident\u2014did not identify any information that would suggest the theft of the aircraft was related to wider criminal activity or terrorist ideology. Although investigators received information regarding Russell's background, possible stressors, and personal life, no element provided a clear motivation for Russell's actions.\"<ref name=FBI/>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n\nRichard Russell was a Horizon Air [[Pushback|ground service agent]] from [[Sumner, Washington]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |title=Seattle: stolen plane crashes after rogue take-off from Sea-Tac airport |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/11/seatac-airport-seattle-plane-takes-off-without-permission |newspaper=The Guardian |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> He had been part of a [[Pushback|tow]] team, which repositions aircraft on the [[airport apron]], for about four years.<ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/ground-service-suicide-horizon-air-seatac-hijacker-plane-1069656 |title=ALASKA AIRLINES: EVERYTHING WE KNOW ABOUT THE SUICIDAL HIJACKER |last=Kogan |first=Danielle |date=August 11, 2018 |website=Newsweek |access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> An operational supervisor for Horizon Air described Russell as \"a quiet guy\" who was \"well liked by the other workers\".<ref name=quiet/> During his communication with air traffic control Russell made a complaint about wages, stating: \"Minimum wage, we'll chalk it up to that. Maybe that will grease some gears a little bit with the higher-ups.\"<ref name=st19>{{cite web|url =https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/he-was-a-jokester-who-complained-about-his-job-but-friends-still-baffled-by-richard-russells-airplane-heist/|title =Richard Russell was a jokester who complained about work, but Sea-Tac plane heist still baffles friends|website =The Seattle Times|first1 =David|last1 =Gutman|first2 =Hal|last2 =Bernton|date =August 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRussell was born in [[Key West, Florida]], and moved to [[Wasilla, Alaska]], at the age of seven.<ref name=quiet>{{cite news |title=Man who took Horizon Air plane from Sea-Tac Airport was quiet, well liked, says former co-worker |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/man-who-took-horizon-air-plane-from-sea-tac-airport-was-quiet-well-liked-says-former-co-worker/ |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Wasilla High School]], where he wrestled and competed in track and field.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/08/12/family-man-who-stole-plane-at-sea-tac-express-shock-others-say-beebo-was-friendly-guy.html|title =Family of man who stole plane at Sea-Tac express 'shock,' others say 'Beebo' was friendly guy|publisher =Fox News|first =Bradford|last =Betz|date =August 12, 2018}}</ref>\nHe was known as \"Beebo\" to his friends and family.<ref name=time/> He had been married since 2012; he met his wife in 2011 at a [[Campus Crusade for Christ]] meeting at [[Southwestern Oregon Community College]]. Together they started a bakery in [[North Bend, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theworldlink.com/new-bakery-is-a-labor-of-love/article_b19316e0-7ce6-11e1-bc81-001a4bcf887a.html |title=New bakery is a labor of love |author=Staff writer(s) |website=[[The World (Coos Bay)|The World]] |date=April 2, 2012}}</ref> They sold the bakery in 2015 so his wife could be closer to her family; they settled in Sumner, Washington, and Russell found employment with Horizon Air.<ref name=time>{{cite web|url =http://time.com/5364913/richard-russel-seattle-horizon-air-stolen-plane/|title ='Beebo Was Loved By Everyone.' Family Left Heartbroken After Airline Worker Steals and Crashes Plane|website =Time|first =Alix|last =Langone|date =August 12, 2018}}</ref>\nHe was an avid traveler and attended [[Washington State University Global Campus]], majoring in social science. He had planned to seek a management position at Horizon Air or become a military officer after receiving his degree.<ref name=heavy5>{{cite web |url=https://heavy.com/news/2018/08/richard-russell-rich-seatac-beebo/ |title=Richard Russell, 'Rich': 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |author=Jessica McBride |publisher=Heavy.com}}</ref> He was active in his church and a leader in the local Christian youth ministry [[Young Life]].<ref name=quiet/>\n\nHorizon Air CEO Gary Beck stated that, as far as the company knew, Russell did not have a [[pilot's license]]. Beck said the aerial maneuvers were \"incredible\" and that he \"did not know how [Russell] achieved the experience that he did.\"<ref name=CBS>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/richard-russell-seatac-horizon-air-stolen-plane-crash-seatac-airport-authorities-no-pilot-license-2018-08-11/  |title=Authorities don't believe man who stole plane had a pilot's license |publisher=CBS |accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> During his conversation with air traffic control, Russell said he \"[knew] what [he was] doing a little bit\" because he had experience playing video games.<ref name=heavy5/> After the incident, Joel Monteith, a pilot for [[SkyWest Airlines]], relayed to an emergency dispatcher that in 2017 he saw Russell and another man \"pointing and flipping switches\" in the cockpit of a SkyWest aircraft parked at Sea\u2013Tac Airport. Monteith stated the men told him they were training to use the aircraft's [[auxiliary power unit]] so they could tow it, but said it was \"suspicious\" that they left when he confronted them. Monteith also recalled that Russell had been in the cockpit of an [[Embraer E-Jet family#E175|Embraer 175]] with him, and that Russell asked him about his \"flows, which is the preflight preparation I do for takeoff.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/pilot-became-suspicious-of-richard-russell-a-year-before-he-stole-airplane-from-sea-tac/|title =\u2018Airplane of opportunity\u2019? Richard Russell raised pilot's suspicions a year before Sea-Tac plane heist|first =Lewis|last =Kamb|website =The Seattle Times|date =September 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the incident, observers on internet forums began referring to Russell as \"Sky King\" as a tribute to his ability at flying the aircraft, as well as his actions during the incident.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Glenn |title=The Sky King of Sea-Tac Airport |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/gb/blog/acquainted-the-night/201809/the-sky-king-sea-tac-airport |website=[[Psychology Today]] |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRussell's family released a statement on August 11, stating they were \"stunned and heartbroken\" and \"devastated by the events\".<ref name=\"Family statement\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/who-was-richard-russell-things-know/DDH7SU1hCUPNgmFEyWSfYO/ |title=Who was Richard Russell? 7 things to know  |last=D'Angelo |first=Bob |date=August 12, 2018 |website=AJC |access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nIn the days after the crash, clean up and recovery crews contracted by Alaska Airlines and their insurers were present on the island to remove debris. As of 2019, this clean up effort was still ongoing with pieces of aircraft wreckage still being located on the island after the first anniversary of the incident. Residents of the island bore some of the cost for cleaning up, and as of 2019 negotiations were under way for their reimbursement by Alaska Airlines insurers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/one-year-after-stolen-horizon-plane-crash-scars-remain-on-ketron-island/ar-AAFy232|title=One year after stolen Horizon plane crash, scars remain on Ketron Island|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2003 Angola 727 disappearance]], another (presumed) instance of aircraft theft\n*[[1999 Air Botswana ATR 42 crash]], an instance of an employee stealing an aircraft and crashing it\n\n{{Portalbar|United States|Aviation}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LeYVtVg6aGs Compilation of footage of the aircraft being flown erratically in the vicinity of Seattle, and the pursuing F-15s]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-GzroZxwhJg ATC Recording]\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horizon Air Q400 incident}}\n[[Category:2018 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:2018 in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Bombardier Dash 8]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents involving deliberate crashes]]\n[[Category:August 2018 crimes in North America]]\n[[Category:August 2018 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the United States in 2018]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Washington (state)]]\n", "name_user": "66.235.11.156", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIncident)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_Horizon_Air_Q400_incident"}
{"title_page": "Carape\u00e7os", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name = Carape\u00e7os\n|image_shield = BCL-carapecos.png\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[C\u00e1vado (intermunicipal community)|C\u00e1vado]]\n|district           = [[Braga District|Braga]]\n|municipality       = [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]]\n|area_total = 8.12\n|population_total = 2277\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|coordinates   = {{coord|41.584|-8.633|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Carape\u00e7os''' is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] ''[[freguesia]]'' (\"civil parish\"), located in the municipality of [[Barcelos Municipality, Portugal|Barcelos]]. The population in 2011 was 2,277,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 8.12&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Barcelos}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carapecos}}\n[[Category:Parishes of Barcelos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{braga-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name = Carape\u00e7os\n|image_shield = BCL-carapecos.png\n|region             = Norte\n|CIM                = [[C\u00e1vado (intermunicipal community)|C\u00e1vado]]\n|district           = [[Braga District|Braga]]\n|municipality       = [[Barcelos, Portugal|Barcelos]]\n|area_total = 8.12\n|population_total = 2277\n|population_as_of = 2011\n|coordinates   = {{coord|41.584|-8.633|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Carape\u00e7os''' is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] ''[[freguesia]]'' (\"civil parish\"), located in the municipality of [[Barcelos Municipality, Portugal|Barcelos]]. The population in 2011 was 2,277,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]</ref> in an area of 8.12&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Barcelos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carapecos}}\n[[Category:Parishes of Barcelos, Portugal]]\n\n\n{{braga-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carape%C3%A7os"}
{"title_page": "Caramujeira", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}}{{advert|date=December 2017}}}}\n\n[[File:Praia da Marinha (2012-09-27), by Klugschnacker in Wikipedia (86).JPG|thumb|250px|[[Praia da Marinha|Marinha Beach]], in Caramujeira, near the city of [[Lagoa, Algarve|Lagoa]], in [[Algarve]] region, [[Portugal]].]]\n'''Caramujeira''' is one of the most luxurious [[hamlet (place)|hamlets]] of [[Portugal]], located in the civil parish of [[Lagoa e Carvoeiro|Lagoa and Carvoeiro]], on the outskirts of the city of [[Lagoa, Algarve|Lagoa]], in the [[Algarve]] region. Became well known for including in its location the internationally famous [[Praia da Marinha|Marinha Beach]], considered by the [[Michelin Guide]] as one of the 10 most beautiful beaches in [[Europe]] and as one of the 100 most beautiful beaches in the world.<ref>[http://fugas.publico.pt/Noticias/291139_praia-da-marinha-um-postal-do-sul P\u00fablico Newspaper], ''Beach of the Navy, a postcard from the South'', Andreia Marques Pereira, 2011.</ref> It is also known for its [[wine]] production.\n\nIn its vicinity are located the touristic villages of [[Benagil]], [[Carvoeiro (Lagoa)|Carvoeiro]] and [[Porches (Lagoa)|Porches]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Carvoeiro (Lagoa)|Carvoeiro]]\n* [[Lagoa, Algarve]]\n* [[Tourism in Portugal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.travel-in-portugal.com/beaches/praia-da-marinha.htm Beach of Caramujeira - Lagoa, Algarve]\n\n{{coord missing|Portugal}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caramujeira}}\n[[Category:Lagoa, Algarve]]\n\n\n{{Faro-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=December 2017}}{{advert|date=December 2017}}}}\n\n[[File:Praia da Marinha (2012-09-27), by Klugschnacker in Wikipedia (86).JPG|thumb|250px|[[Praia da Marinha|Marinha Beach]], in Caramujeira, near the city of [[Lagoa, Algarve|Lagoa]], in [[Algarve]] region, [[Portugal]].]]\n'''Caramujeira''' is one of the most luxurious [[hamlet (place)|hamlets]] of [[Portugal]], located in the civil parish of [[Lagoa e Carvoeiro|Lagoa and Carvoeiro]], on the outskirts of the city of [[Lagoa, Algarve|Lagoa]], in the [[Algarve]] region. Became well known for including in its location the internationally famous [[Praia da Marinha|Marinha Beach]], considered by the [[Michelin Guide]] as one of the 10 most beautiful beaches in [[Europe]] and as one of the 100 most beautiful beaches in the world.<ref>[http://fugas.publico.pt/Noticias/291139_praia-da-marinha-um-postal-do-sul P\u00fablico Newspaper], ''Beach of the Navy, a postcard from the South'', Andreia Marques Pereira, 2011.</ref> It is also known for its [[wine]] production.\n\nIn its vicinity are located the touristic villages of [[Benagil]], [[Carvoeiro (Lagoa)|Carvoeiro]] and [[Porches (Lagoa)|Porches]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Carvoeiro (Lagoa)|Carvoeiro]]\n* [[Lagoa, Algarve]]\n* [[Tourism in Portugal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.travel-in-portugal.com/beaches/praia-da-marinha.htm Beach of Caramujeira - Lagoa, Algarve]\n\n{{coord missing|Portugal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caramujeira}}\n[[Category:Lagoa, Algarve]]\n\n{{Faro-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caramujeira"}
